Hanss [i.e. Hanns] Eisler leaves U.S. [graphic] ; Hanss [sic] Eisler, composer and brother of Gerhart Eisler, alleged no. 1 Communist in the U.S., speaks with his wife, Anna Louise, at LaGuardia Field, before their departure from the U.S., March 26th. A deportation order against Eisler, a native of Germany and citizen of Austria, was issued last month after he admitted membership in the German Communist party prior to his arrival in the U.S. in 1940. The order was stayed, however, to permit him to leave the country voluntarily.

Briton receives medal for merit [graphic] ; Sir William S. Stephenson (second from right), wartime British security coordinator for the Western hermisphere, receives the Medal for Merit, highest honor the United States can grant a non-citizen, Nov. 30, in a New York ceremony. Presentation of the medal is made by Major General William J. Donovan (left), wartime chief of the Office of Strategic Services, in the presence of Col. G. Turkey pushes modernization [graphic] ; Not since the United States as a struggling young American republic founded Washington as the national capital, has there been such an ambitious attempt as that of Mustapha Kemal, president of the new Turkish republic, to found a real Turkish capital at Angora. Although the financial condition of the country is poor, Mustapha Kemal has gone ahead with his modernizing program and already has achieved a noticeable improvement in the buildings and streets of the city.

Capital of modern Turkey [graphic] ; This photo shows one of the main streets of Ankara, the capital of Turkey since 1923. This is one of the cities President Eisenhower will visit on his forthcoing good-will tour of ten countries. The sweeping lines of Ankara's new buildings and its well-planned thoroughfares exemplify the dynamic, progressive spirit of modern Turkey. Three decades ago, Ankara was a small, slumbering provincial town with two thousand years of history behind it. Now it is a modern city with a population of 350,000 and is still growing. Situated in the center of the country, Ankara is snow-covered in winter and has dry, invigorating summers.

Turkey pushes modernization [graphic] ; Not since the United States as a struggling young American republic founded Washington as the national capital, has there been such an ambitious attempt as that of Mustapha Kemal, president of the new Turkish republic to found a real Turkish capital at Angora, 200 miles from the sea, on a mountain plateau of Anatolia, the original home of the Turks.

Grim reminder in Ankara [graphic] ; This super-bomb, placed before a statue depicting a peasant of the Turkish National Revolution in 1919-22, is regarded as a token to the people of the Turkish capital of what modern warfare would mean. This grim display was seen at Ankara less than two weeks ago. On Oct. 28, as Italian troops pushed across the Albanian border into Greece, it took on an even grimmer aspect. Turkey regards Greece as her friend and has said that she would consider an invasion of Greece a threat to the Dardanelles.
